The primary use case is to negate filter expressions using `FilterHelper.negate(operand)`. This is useful for implementing 'not' conditions in filters. Additionally, `FilterHelper.expandIn` and `FilterHelper.expandNin` can be used to convert IN and NIN expressions into equivalent expressions using OR/EQ or AND/NE, respectively, which is helpful for vector stores that don't natively support IN/NIN operations. For example:

```java
Filter.Operand negatedFilter = FilterHelper.negate(filter);
FilterExpressionBuilder builder = new FilterExpressionBuilder();
Filter.Operand inFilter = builder.in("country", "UK", "NL");
